<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
Perennial creeper or climber. Stems up to 3 m, densely covered with long (&gt; 0.5 mm), upright, whitish trichomes. Petioles 1.5-4 cm long, indumentum like on stem. Leaves 3-10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-11 cm, 5-lobate. Lobes obovate or elliptical in outline, rarely ovate. Margin lobulate or coarsely serrate, (at maturity pale brownish) dentate (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. a Ripening fruit of Coccinia hirtella. Note the typical lobulate leaves of this species in the lower right b Ripening fruit of Coccinia sessilifolia. The fruit, like the plant, bears a waxy bloom c Ripening fruits of Coccinia megarrhiza have a dark green halo around the white longitudinal mottling. The left fruit is derived from pollination with Coccinia megarrhiza pollen, whereas the smaller fruit on the right is derived from cross-pollination with Coccinia trilobata (both pollinations were conducted on the same day)." pageId="81" pageNumber="82">13a</figureCitation>
). If margin serrate then lobe tips acute, else often rounded. Upper and lower leaf surface, esp. on the nerves, densely covered with long, upright, whitish trichomes. Probracts up to 3 mm. Tendrils simple or bifid. Male flowers solitary, rarely in few-flowered raceme. Common peduncle 1.8-4.5 cm, with white trichomes, pedicel of racemous flowers 0.2-3 cm, with white trichomes. Bracts up to 2 mm, caducous. Pedicel of solitary flowers 3-8.5 cm, with white trichomes. Perianth tube with white trichomes. Calyx lobes narrow triangulate to lineal, 3.5-6.5 mm long, spreading. Corolla 2-3.7 cm long, buff, lobes 1-2 cm. Filament column white, anther head pale yellowish, pollen sacs yellow to orange. Female flowers one solitary. Pedicel 0.5-5.5 cm, with long, white trichomes. Hypanthium with white trichomes, calyx lobes and corolla like in male flowers. Style columnar, whitish. Stigma bulging, yellow. Ovary with some long trichomes. Fruit oblong ovoid, 5-6 cm 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-3 cm, sparsely covered with long trichomes to glabrous, ripening from green via green with longitudinal whitish mottling, via yellow, orange to red when ripe (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. a Ripening fruit of Coccinia hirtella. Note the typical lobulate leaves of this species in the lower right b Ripening fruit of Coccinia sessilifolia. The fruit, like the plant, bears a waxy bloom c Ripening fruits of Coccinia megarrhiza have a dark green halo around the white longitudinal mottling. The left fruit is derived from pollination with Coccinia megarrhiza pollen, whereas the smaller fruit on the right is derived from cross-pollination with Coccinia trilobata (both pollinations were conducted on the same day)." pageId="81" pageNumber="82">13a</figureCitation>
). Seeds 5.5-6.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-3.5 mm (L/W), seed height not seen, rather symmetrically obovate, face flatly lenticular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Flowering time: January-April, September, November, December.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
